Sorry that I understand the issue wrong initially. I initially though for some browser element focus is not called due to a recent change.

The issue is more related to the way we implement text editing functionality for Flutter for Web. Flutter Web engine uses a native DOM element (input element or text area element) for text editing. Flutter Web Engine receives information (ex: location, style, autocomplete info) from the Framework. Using this information, engine creates a form, created input elements and appends them to the dom. Later it calls `focus()` on the DOM element. 

Unfortunately, when element is created on the fly like this, the "autofill context menu" does not appear. The menu only appears a user, clicks on an element.

For example a javascript which (over) simplifies the operations we perform on the DOM, won't also open the "autofill menu". Only after the user clicks on this DOM element, browser shows the menu.

```
  var form = document.createElement("form");
  var input1 = document.createElement("input");
  var input2 = document.createElement("input");
  input1.name = 'name';
  input2.name = 'organization';
  input1.autocomplete = 'name';
  input2.autocomplete = 'organization';
  input1.text = 'text';
  input2.text = 'text';
  form.appendChild(input1);
  form.appendChild(input2);
  document.body.append(form);
  input1.focus();
```

