Facing the same issue on iOS. However if you look at the description of TextInputType.name you can see:

>  /// Optimized for a person's name.
  ///
  /// On iOS, requests the
  /// [UIKeyboardType.namePhonePad](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/uikit/uikeyboardtype/namephonepad)
  /// keyboard, a keyboard optimized for entering a person’s name or phone number.
  /// Does not support auto-capitalization.
  ///
  /// On Android, requests a keyboard optimized for
  /// [TYPE_TEXT_VARIATION_PERSON_NAME](https://developer.android.com/reference/android/text/InputType#TYPE_TEXT_VARIATION_PERSON_NAME).

Notice the part where it says 

>   /// Does not support auto-capitalization.

Most likely not a bug then, just a limitation. Although a bit of a weird one to me. Usually when you fill in a name, lets say just the First Name, you expect to at least start with a capital letter.

So there are 3 solutions that I can think of:

1. Don't use `TextInputType.name`, you can leave it empty so that it will fall back to `TextInputType.text` or `TextInputType.multiline` depending whether you have max lines set to 1 or more. Disadvantage here is obvious.. the user will be able to use all keyboard characters/symbols but you need to validate/format this anyways. You can't trust the user, they could've used a USB keyboard anyways.
2. Keep `TextInputType.name`, but add an inputformatter where you format the first letter to uppercase. See my example below. This solution is not perfect because it does not capitalise each word (its possible though) and when the user sees the soft keyboard on iOS, the SHIFT button is not activated thus the user will assume that the first letter is lowercased which is not true anymore. Also, if a user really wants to have their first letter lowercased it's simply impossible now.
```
inputFormatters: <TextInputFormatter>[
  TextInputFormatter.withFunction(
    (oldValue, newValue) {
      // Returns the new value after converting the first character to uppercase
      if (newValue.text.isNotEmpty) {
        return newValue.replaced(
          const TextRange(start: 0, end: 1),
          newValue.text.substring(0, 1).toUpperCase(),
        );
      }
      return newValue;
    },
  )
],
```
3. Best solution would be to take a better look at Flutter's source code, make sure to understand whether this was intentional or a bug, and create a PR here with the fix. This would be my recommendation, however I took the shortcut with option 2 😨 .

